ation, etc.: FTX just thought =E2=80=9Cah well if a token=E2=80=99s price g=
oes up then it=E2=80=99s valuable and we can lend against it,=E2=80=9D so t=
hey did, without checking to see if the prices made sense or learning lesso=
ns when they didn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
But another possibility is what we talked about in the previous section:=C2=
=A0None of this made any sense.=C2=A0Bitcoin is worth $17,000; it has no ca=
sh flows and someone just made it up within recent memory. Ethereum, Dogeco=
in, etc. Essentially all of the assets in crypto trade on sentiment, and it=
 is incoherent to say =E2=80=9Cwell Bitcoin is really worth $17,000 so I wi=
ll lend against it at a high loan-to-value ratio, while MobileCoin is not r=
eally worth $70 so I won=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D If you are in the business of =
lending against crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0more broadly, if you are in the busin=
ess of promising safety in crypto, as  FTX was=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then it =
is easy to end up lending billions of real dollars against a pile of collat=
eral that doesn=E2=80=99t make sense. In part due to adverse selection =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0if the collateral is worth so much, why are they using it to bo=
rrow from you? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in part because no pile of crypto collate=
ral is ever going to make complete sense.

