</a>=C2=A0But Davies gives an account of the=C2=A0<em>rise=C2=A0</em>of 3AC=
 that is quite useful as just a general story of what happened in crypto ov=
er the last few years, and I want to talk about it here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">3AC started as a small proprietary trading fir=
m doing simple arbitrages in foreign-exchange trading. One bank would offer=
 to sell a currency at $1.0001, and another would bid to buy it at $1.0002,=
 and 3AC would buy from one and sell to the other at the same time and make=
 a risk-free profit of a =E2=80=9Cpip=E2=80=9D ($0.0001) or two.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After a while, 3AC got into crypto, because yo=
u could make much larger risk-free-ish profits in crypto by buying Bitcoin =
on one exchange and simultaneously selling it at a higher price on another =
exchange. This again looks like a real arbitrage =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDEvdGhlLWV4LWphbm=
Utc3RyZWV0LXRyYWRlci13aG8tcy1idWlsZGluZy1hLW11bHRpLWJpbGxpb24tY3J5cHRvLWVtc=
GlyZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB48775c1b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the origin story</a> of Bankman-F=
ried=E2=80=99s Alameda Research too, arbitraging Japanese Bitcoin prices =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0though it is a stretch to call it =E2=80=9Crisk-free.=E2=80=
=9D The main risk is that one or both of the crypto exchanges might disappe=
ar with your money, which was a common thing for crypto exchanges to do in =
the early days of crypto, and which has come back in vogue recently.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another important arbitrage is the Bitcoin spo=
t/futures arbitrage. In the early days of Bitcoin futures, people would pay=
 much more to own Bitcoin futures than they would to own Bitcoin directly.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMTctMTItMTkvYml0Y29pbi1mdXR1cmVzLWFyZS1hLWdyZWF0LXdheS10by1ub3Qtb3duLWJpdG=
NvaW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce06f9ef" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about various reasons</a> f=
or this =E2=80=94=C2=A0owning Bitcoin directly exposes you to the risk of f=
orgetting your private key, for instance, and is administratively alarming =
for a lot of traditional financial institutions =E2=80=94=C2=A0but one simp=
le one is that if you want to buy a Bitcoin you have to have $17,000, while=
 if you want to buy a Bitcoin futures contract=C2=A0you can generally put u=
p much less money for the same amount of Bitcoin exposure. The main intuiti=
on behind the spot/futures arbitrage was basically that there was a lot of =
demand for Bitcoin, and it was expensive for crypto investors to=C2=A0<em>g=
et dollars</em>, so a Bitcoin product that required fewer dollars was more =
attractive than one that required a lot of dollars.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And 3AC did this arbitrage by, basically, bein=
g pretty good at borrowing money. You find someone to lend you money at 10%=
 interest, you use the borrowed money to buy Bitcoin, you sell Bitcoin futu=
res at a 30% premium, you collect 20%, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another important trade is the Grayscale arbit=
rage, in which a firm like 3AC buys or borrows some Bitcoin, delivers them =
to Grayscale Investments LLC, and gets back shares of the <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly9ncmF5c2N=
hbGUuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2dyYXlzY2FsZS1iaXRjb2luLXRydXN0Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB5d6c834a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> Grayscale Bitcoin Trust</a>, or GBTC.=C2=A0GBTC =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0like Bitcoin futures =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a way to own Bitcoin =
without actually owning Bitcoin, and it was friendly to traditional retail =
and institutional investors in a way that owning Bitcoin directly, or even =
owning most futures products, was not. So GBTC=C2=A0consistently traded at =
a premium to its net asset value for years: One share of GBTC might represe=
nt $12 worth of Bitcoin, but would trade at $15. A fund like 3AC could deli=
ver $12 million worth of Bitcoin to Grayscale and get back 1 million shares=
, with a net asset value of $12 million (equal to what 3AC delivered) but a=
 market value of $15 million, for a free $3 million profit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This looks like an arbitrage but has a problem=
, which is that =E2=80=94=C2=A0for securities-law reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0yo=
u don=E2=80=99t get the shares for a year. You can turn your $12 million of=
 Bitcoin into $15 million of Grayscale, but you have to wait a year. This m=
eans that it is not a risk-free trade: It is a=C2=A0one-year=C2=A0bet on=C2=
=A0<em>the Grayscale premium</em>. If you buy (or borrow) $12 million worth=
 of Bitcoin and deliver it to Grayscale for one million shares in a year, a=
nd in a year the price of Bitcoin is constant, but now instead of trading a=
t a premium to Bitcoin Grayscale trades at a discount, then you will only g=
et back, say, $10 million from selling your shares, and you will have lost =
$2 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact that happened; GBTC has traded at =
a discount to spot Bitcoin for much of the last two years.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What could cause this? It could have become le=
ss appealing for investors to hold Grayscale, or more appealing for them to=
 hold Bitcoin directly. But another answer, one that Davies emphasizes, is =
that=C2=A0<em>it became much cheaper for crypto hedge funds to borrow money=
</em>. This is a trade that offered big profits if you could borrow money, =
buy Bitcoin, deliver the Bitcoin to Grayscale, and wait a year. If you were=
 early to this trade, you did well. But then everyone noticed it and starte=
d doing it, which meant lots of crypto hedge funds were creating lots of ne=
w GBTC shares, which meant that the supply of new GBTC shares (created by h=
edge funds) outstripped the demand (from retail buyers). If you got into th=
e trade when it was relatively quiet and GBTC traded at a premium, and then=
 a year later the trade was crowded and GBTC traded at a discount, you lost=
 a lot of money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Grayscale trades got more crowded, 3AC look=
ed into other sorts of arbitrages. The Grayscale trade is risky, but it sor=
t of has the=C2=A0<em>shape=C2=A0</em>of an arbitrage trade; if you squint,=
 it is =E2=80=9Cbuy Bitcoin and sell Bitcoin futures,=E2=80=9D only instead=
 of Bitcoin futures it is future delivery of Grayscale shares. But once you=
=E2=80=99ve done that trade you might squint further and do some trades tha=
t are even less arbitrage-y. Davies talks about =E2=80=9Cdiscounted Layer 1=
s.=E2=80=9D The trade is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone is launching some blockchain =
protocol, some crypto network like Avalanche or Solana that is intended to =
compete with Ethereum.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To raise mo=
ney to build out the ecosystem, they sell tokens to investors.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For legal reasons, there is a long lockup peri=
od on the tokens: If you buy the tokens in the ICO, you can=E2=80=99t sell =
them for a year or more.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But you g=
et to buy the tokens at a discount of 40% to 50%.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there are some tokens that are supposed to =
be worth $10,=C2=A0that probably have a trading price of $10, though perhap=
s on small volume and without much history. And you get to buy a lot of the=
m for=C2=A0$6; you just can=E2=80=99t sell them for a year. Davies<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you believe the market=E2=80=99s going up, =
if you believe in this protocol, if you believe that they can take those do=
llars and do marketing or build their platform or=C2=A0hire more people and=
 build value, then it looks like a very attractive trade. And so for us, we=
 found several protocols that we liked, we did very sizeable amounts with t=
hem, and that became another source of,=C2=A0you know, something that sat i=
n the middle, where I=C2=A0would have considered it somewhat like an arb ki=
nd of trade, like it is a discount, but it=E2=80=99s very directional. It=
=E2=80=99s not like you=E2=80=99re punting Bitcoin, but it=E2=80=99s somewh=
ere in the middle. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over time, people end up doing more and more o=
f this kind of thing, and then by the end, you know, when credit gets squee=
zed out of the system, there=E2=80=99s a collapse. Basically that=E2=80=99s=
 what happened.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I confess that a certain amount of steam came =
out my ears when I heard this. Here Davies is describing taking, essentiall=
y,=C2=A0<em>equity=C2=A0</em>risk on new crypto protocols. (Worse than equi=
ty risk; the token of some new crypto protocol probably has fewer legal rig=
hts and cash-flow claims than a share of stock.) He is making multi-year, i=
lliquid, unhedgeable speculative investments in brand-new crypto protocols =
because he thinks =E2=80=9Cthe market=E2=80=99s going up=E2=80=9D and becau=
se he hopes that those protocols can hire people and build value. This is a=
 venture capital investment.=C2=A0And he describes it as an=C2=A0<em>arbitr=
age</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which, you know, fine, whatever. People are al=
lowed to be wrong; hedge funds are allowed to lose money. But the thing tha=
t happened with 3AC is not just that it made a long slow transition from pi=
cking up pips in high-frequency foreign exchange trading to making multi-ye=
ar venture bets on new crypto protocols because it liked the founders. It=
=E2=80=99s also that it kept the same financing model the whole time. 3AC s=
tarted out as a proprietary trading firm that made short-term arbitrage-y b=
ets, turned over its capital frequently and had a very high Sharpe ratio, s=
o it was able to borrow a lot of money. It ended up as a firm making long-t=
erm unhedgeable illiquid equity bets on crypto protocols with no track reco=
rds, and was somehow able to borrow even more money. Davies describes his r=
elationship with his lenders, firms =E2=80=94=C2=A0like Voyager or Celsius =
or BlockFi =E2=80=94=C2=A0that I have described as =E2=80=9Ccrypto shadow b=
anks=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These firms are under pressure to lend out mor=
e and more too. You have to remember that the way they make money is they t=
ake these deposits, they lend them out, they earn the spread, but they=E2=
=80=99re raising equity valuations. And some of these firms are raising at =
three =E2=80=A6=C2=A0one of the firms raised at a $14 billion valuation, ot=
hers at $3 plus billion valuations. They really want to lend this money out=
. They can=E2=80=99t afford for it to sit on the books, for one. They don=
=E2=80=99t want to return it. So their risk management also starts to go do=
wn. And, you know, that becomes the whole system, basically.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think one of the last calls we did someone l=
ent me high nine figures, almost a billion, off a phone call. That was the =
final one, that was, like,=C2=A0uncollateralized. That=E2=80=99s where the =
system was. People needed to get dollars out the door. We were a hedge fund=
, we were paid to take risk.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Were they? One point emphasized in the intervi=
ew is that 3AC was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>really a hedge fund, but a propri=
etary trading firm; for the most part, it did not take outside money and us=
ed its partners=E2=80=99 capital. Nobody was paying 3AC to take risks with =
their money. Instead, 3AC was paying other people =E2=80=94=C2=A0its lender=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0interest to borrow money. Those lenders presumably did=C2=
=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>want 3AC to take risks with their money; they wanted t=
o get paid back; they wanted their money to be safe. But they faced competi=
tive pressures to lend a bunch of money to 3AC, so they did.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The story that I want to tell here is that the=
re was an intense demand,=C2=A0<em>within crypto</em>, for =E2=80=9Csafe as=
sets.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CSafe assets,=E2=80=9D in this context, means places=
 to invest your cryptocurrency or stablecoins that=C2=A0<em>earn interest</=
em>, that feel like bank accounts rather than speculative investments. You =
might put your dollars into a crypto shadow bank, exchange them for dollar-=
denominated stablecoins, and earn 8% interest (in dollar-indexed stablecoin=
s) rather than the 0% you=E2=80=99d get at a real bank. Or you might own Bi=
tcoin, and think Bitcoin is pretty safe, and want to earn 8% interest on yo=
ur Bitcoin. But what you didn=E2=80=99t want is to guess which small-time c=
ryptocurrencies would win or lose; you did not want to make speculative bet=
s on individual cryptocurrencies. You wanted to own normal understandable s=
tuff (dollars, perhaps Bitcoins) and get paid a lot of interest for partici=
pating in =E2=80=9Ccrypto.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto had no sensible way to manufacture this=
 interest. There were not a lot of people borrowing Bitcoin or stablecoins =
to buy houses or build factories or whatever. Crypto shadow banks could not=
 lend their crypto at 12% interest to stable companies secured by real-worl=
d collateral; everything in crypto was new, and financial, and on the block=
chain. The best the shadow banks could do was lend their crypto to well-reg=
arded crypto hedge funds secured by crypto collateral, though even that bec=
ame rarer as lending got more competitive and shadow banks did more unsecur=
ed loans.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at least, the shadow banks thought, they w=
ere lending the money to hedge funds who were doing=C2=A0<em>safe trades</e=
m>. They weren=E2=80=99t lending money to firms like 3AC to make wild specu=
lative bets on random cryptocurrencies. They were lending money to 3AC to d=
o =E2=80=9Carbitrages.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And then you sit down with Kyle Davies=
 and ask him what kind of arbitrages he did and he=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9C=
well we=E2=80=99d take four-year lockups on illiquid unhedgeable tokens of =
brand-new protocols, but we=E2=80=99d get a discount, so it was kind of an =
arbitrage.=E2=80=9D Oops!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In recent months I have often thought, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIyLXRoZS1jcnlwdG8tc3RvcnkvP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDEyMDUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZiNyZWludmVudGluZy=
0yMDA4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc4c4d516" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  and written</a>, that =
the crypto industry in 2022 rediscovered the 2008 financial crisis. A quick=
 summary of 2008 is that there was a lot of demand for safe assets, for bon=
ds with AAA ratings. The financial system obligingly manufactured those ass=
ets, taking risky assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0mostly subprime mortgages =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and packaging and slicing them to achieve AAA ratings. There was so m=
uch demand for safe assets that the manufacturing process got sloppy: The s=
ubprime mortgages got ever more subprime, the slicing and repackaging got l=
ess effective, and ultimately some of the safe assets turned out not to be =
safe.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Something like that seems to have happened in =
crypto but there is a critical difference. In crypto, there are no mortgage=
s=C2=A0to speak of. You cannot really start by taking some somewhat risky c=
ash flows and tranching them to make some of the cash flows safer. There ar=
e no cash flows. The safe assets in crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0interest-bearing =
accounts at Voyager or Celsius or BlockFi or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRl=
bnQvMzI5NzdhOTktYzFjMy00ZjM0LTllY2MtNDA1NzIxN2JmOTc0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB4ef0a024" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> Gemini</a> =E2=80=94 are created by making unsecured =
billion-dollar loans, negotiated in a single phone call, to arbitrage tradi=
ng firms that are actually just making long-term bets on the marketing abil=
ities of blockchain entrepreneurs. Crypto shadow banks did not manufacture =
safe assets out of risky investments; they just relabeled the risky investm=
ents as safe assets. There were people taking wild speculative risks on bra=
nd-new, sentiment-driven crypto projects, and there were people who wanted =
to invest safely and earn 8%, and they were the same people.</p>
