-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Meanwhile, FTX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sam Bankman-Fried continues his sad press tour=
, but his explanations of what happened to FTX=E2=80=99s customers=E2=80=99=
 money remain unsatisfying. Here is the version that Bankman-Fried seems to=
 be settling on; it is infuriatingly simple:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Customers deposited several billion d=
ollars into FTX=C2=A0<em>through=C2=A0</em>Alameda: For weird bank-access r=
easons, FTX couldn=E2=80=99t accept some wire transfers from customers, so =
the customers transferred their money to Alameda Research, FTX=E2=80=99s af=
filiated trading firm, instead, and Alameda passed it on to FTX. (This woul=
d be a huge red flag even if nothing else went wrong!)</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Alameda sent the money to FTX, which credited it to cu=
stomers, but they somehow forgot to debit it from Alameda, leading FTX to t=
hink that its customers had the money but also that Alameda had billions of=
 dollars more than it actually had.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Alameda proceeded to lose the money on dumb trades and lavish spending, b=
ut no one noticed, because (1) they thought Alameda had so much money it di=
dn=E2=80=99t matter and (2) their accounting generally was pretty bad.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This explanation has some virtues. It is fairl=
y simple. It fits well with <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1mdHgtd2FzLW5vdC12=
ZXJ5LWNhcmVmdWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ=
1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leX=
N0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce704440" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  FTX=E2=80=99s new mana=
gement=E2=80=99s exasperation</a> with old management=E2=80=99s sloppy acco=
unting; this=C2=A0<em>is </em>a story of sloppy accounting. And Bankman-Fri=
ed has been telling some version of this story pretty consistently since FT=
X=E2=80=99s collapse; even as he was shopping for a rescuer pre-bankruptcy,=
 he was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.2=
87535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtM=
TQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZG=
JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNSZ=
1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6537a21b" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  sending around a spreadsheet</a> with an $8 billion hole for a =E2=80=9CH=
idden, poorly internally labeled =E2=80=98fiat@=E2=80=99 account.=E2=80=9D =
On the other hand, it is a terrible explanation? =E2=80=9COh that $8 billio=
n, we sort of weren=E2=80=99t paying attention to it, so we spent it on sna=
cks=E2=80=9D? I don=E2=80=99t know. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjItMTItMDIvaW5zaWRlLXNhbS1iYW5rbWFuLWZyaWVkLXMtYmFoYW1pYW4t=
cGVudGhvdXNlLWFmdGVyLWZ0eC1zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNS=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3330d1a2" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Zeke Faux went to the Bahamas Contrition Show</a> an=
d came away with this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou misplaced $8 billion?=E2=80=9D I =
ask.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMisaccounted,=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried =
says, sounding almost proud of his explanation. Sometimes, he says, custome=
rs would wire money to Alameda Research instead of sending it directly to F=
TX. (Some banks were more willing to work with the hedge fund than the exch=
ange, for some reason.) He claims that somehow, FTX=E2=80=99s internal acco=
unting system double-counted this money, essentially crediting it to both t=
he exchange and the fund.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That still doesn=E2=80=99t explain why the mon=
ey was gone. =E2=80=9CWhere did the $8 billion go?=E2=80=9D I ask.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To answer, Bankman-Fried creates a new tab on =
the spreadsheet and starts typing. He lists Alameda and FTX=E2=80=99s bigge=
st cash flows. One of the biggest expenses is paying a net $2.5 billion to=
=C2=A0Binance, a rival, to buy out its investment in FTX. He also lists $25=
0 million for real estate, $1.5 billion for expenses, $4 billion for ventur=
e capital investments, $1.5 billion for acquisitions and $1 billion labeled=
 =E2=80=9Cfuckups.=E2=80=9D Even accounting for both firms=E2=80=99 profits=
, and all the venture capital money raised by FTX, it tallies to negative $=
6.5 billion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried is telling me that the billions =
of dollars customers wired to Alameda is gone simply because the companies =
spent way more than they made. He claims he paid so little attention to his=
 expenses that he didn=E2=80=99t realize he was spending more than he was t=
aking in. =E2=80=9CI was real lazy about this mental math,=E2=80=9D the for=
mer physics major says. He creates another column in his spreadsheet and ty=
pes in much lower numbers to show what he thought he was spending at the ti=
me.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, none of the other categories =E2=80=94 $=
2.5 billion of=C2=A0<em>equity buybacks</em>,=C2=A0$250 million for real es=
tate, $1.5 billion for expenses, $4 billion for venture capital and $1.5 bi=
llion for acquisitions =E2=80=94=C2=A0looks=C2=A0<em>good</em>, now. This i=
s not $9.8=C2=A0billion of prudent investments plus some, uh, mistakes. Thi=
s is $9.8=C2=A0billion of mistakes, plus a billion-dollar miscellaneous cat=
egory for the even worse mistakes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wall Street Journal=E2=80=99s Alexander Os=
ipovich also went to see the show; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mdH=
gtZm91bmRlci1zYW0tYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zYXlzLWhlLWNhbnQtYWNjb3VudC1mb3ItYmlsb=
GlvbnMtc2VudC10by1hbGFtZWRhLTExNjcwMTA3NjU5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e5e67=
92" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s what he got</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over time, FTX customers deposited more than $=
5 billion in those Alameda accounts, he said. Now those funds are gone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThey were wired to Alameda, and=E2=80=
=A6I can only speculate about what happened after that,=E2=80=9D Mr. Bankma=
n-Fried told the Journal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDollars are fungible with each other.=
 And so it=E2=80=99s not like there=E2=80=99s this $1 bill over here that y=
ou can trace through from start to finish. What you get is more just omnibu=
s, you know, pots of assets of various forms,=E2=80=9D he added. =E2=80=A6<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s remarks suggest th=
at FTX customer funds flowing into Alameda bank accounts could have been re=
corded in two places=E2=80=94both as FTX customer funds and as part of Alam=
eda=E2=80=99s trading positions. Such double-counting would have created a =
huge hole in FTX=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=99s balance sheets, with asset=
s that weren=E2=80=99t really there. Mr. Bankman-Fried denied that double-c=
ounting affected FTX=E2=80=99s financials=E2=80=94but acknowledged that Ala=
meda=E2=80=99s liabilities might not have been fully recorded.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere are lots of ways that one could=
 have done this in a responsible way,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CClearly wh=
at we did was not one of them.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, super, fine, sure.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, the Financial Times reports on an i=
nteresting <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2989456=
4.287535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNWU5ZGM0MjQtYWVmNC00OTgxLWE0ZD=
ctZTNjNDBlMWU2MDg1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbdcb08a1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Alameda trad=
e from last year</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge fund Alameda Research stepped in to shel=
ter FTX from a loss of up to $1bn after a customer trade on the crypto plat=
form blew up last year, highlighting the deep and longstanding links betwee=
n Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s digital asset companies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda in early 2021 shouldered FTX=E2=80=99s=
 burden when a client=E2=80=99s leveraged bet on an obscure token tore thro=
ugh buffers designed to shield the exchange from sustaining losses when a t=
rade goes bad, according to people with knowledge of the matter.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX lent to traders so they could make big bet=
s on crypto with just a small initial outlay, known as trading on margin. I=
f the traders made losses, FTX would automatically sell the cash or margin =
they had put up, thereby protecting the exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried had touted FTX=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cunique=E2=80=9D liquidation engine, which he argued was a safer way for =
exchanges to manage risk. The 30-year-old had pushed legislators in the US =
to adopt FTX=E2=80=99s system, potentially opening it out to non-crypto mar=
kets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The system included a fail-safe: it incentivis=
ed large trading groups to take over trades where the initial margin was al=
most wiped out. But on the riskiest, most thinly traded tokens, only Alamed=
a was willing to serve as that last line of defence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In April 2021, a crypto token called MobileCoi=
n =E2=80=94 used for payments in the privacy-focused messaging app Signal =
=E2=80=94 suddenly spiked in price from about $6 to almost $70, before cras=
hing back down again almost as quickly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The wild moves came after a trader on FTX had =
built an unusually large position in the little-known token. Two people fam=
iliar with the matter said that when the price rose, the trader used the po=
sition to borrow against it on FTX, potentially a scheme to extract dollars=
 from the exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda was forced to step in and assume the t=
rader=E2=80=99s position to protect FTX. The trading company=E2=80=99s loss=
 on this deal was at least in the hundreds of millions of dollars, the peop=
le said, and as high as $1bn, according to one of the people, wiping out a =
large share of Alameda=E2=80=99s 2021 trading profits.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can read this story as foreshadowing of FT=
X=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=99s ultimate blowup, in a couple of ways. For=
 one thing, one possible story of how Alameda lost its money is that <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29894564.287535/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTUvbWF0dC1sZXZ=
pbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1iaW5hbmNlLWZ0eC1hbmQtY2Fycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA1MjJfTU=
